{{for|the cricket umpire|Akbar Ali (umpire)}} '''Akbar Ali''' ({{lang-kn|ಅಕ್ಬರ್ ಅಲಿ}}; March 3, 1925 &ndash; February 21, 2016) was an Indian [[Kannada]] academic and poet from [[Karnataka]],<ref>[http://www.kamat.com/kalranga/kar/writers/13697.jpg Akbar Ali's photo ]</ref> India.
==Life==
Ali was born to Ameerbi and Appa Saheb from Ullagaddi village of [[Khanapur]], [[Belgaum]] district.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}} He completed his [[Bachelor of Arts]] at the University of Bombay in 1949. He passed the master's degree at Willingdon College [[Sangli]] in 1960. As a lecturer he served in the Arts and Science College of Karwar for 14 years. In 1980, the University of Mysore awarded him with a PhD.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}} His works include ''Nava Chetan'', "Anna", "Sumana Saurabha", "Gandha Kesara", ''Nireeksheyalli'', and ''Vish Sindhu''.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}
He was awarded the ''Sumana Saurabha'' - [[Karnataka State]] [[Sahitya Academy]] award in 1967 and 1984. In 1986, he became a Member of the Karnataka [[Vidhan Parishad]] (Legislative Council).<ref>{{cite book|last=Datta|first=Amaresh |title=The Encyclopaedia Of Indian Literature (Volume One - A To Devo)|publisher=[[Sahitya Akademi]]|year=2006|volume=1|pages=116|isbn=978-81-260-1803-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ObFCT5_taSgC&pg=PA116 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Dutt|first=Kartik Chandra |title=Who's who of Indian Writers, 1999: A-M|publisher=[[Sahitya Akademi]]|year=1999|pages=28–29|isbn=978-81-260-0873-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QA1V7sICaIwC&pg=PA29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/Poet-Akbar-Ali-Known-for-Limericks-Dies-at-91/2016/02/22/article3290386.ece|title=Poet Akbar Ali, Known for Limericks, Dies at 91|work=The New Indian Express}}</ref>
