{{Other uses|Orthology (disambiguation){{!}}Orthology}}

'''Orthology''' is the study of the right use of words in [[language]]. The word comes from [[Greek language|Greek]] ''ortho''- ("correct") and -''logy'' ("science of"). This [[science]] is a place where [[psychology]], [[philosophy]], [[linguistics]], and many other fields of [[learning]] come together. The most noted use of ''Orthology'' is for the selection of words 
for the language of [[Basic English]] by the [[Orthological Institute]].

The book, ''The Meaning of Meaning'', by [[Charles Kay Ogden|C.K. Ogden]] and [[I.A. Richards]], is an important book dealing with orthology. The term ''Orthology'' comes from the book ''The Grammar of Science'' by [[Karl Pearson]].<ref>{{cite book |last= Karl |first= Pearson |title= The Grammar of Science |origyear= 1893 |publisher= Walter Scott |location= London |pages=454 |quote= A fundamental part of logic is the study of the right use of language, clear definition, and, if needful, invention of terms -- ''Orthology''.}}</ref>

