{{distinguish|Yuki language (California)}} {{see also|Mbyá Guaraní language}} {{Infobox language |name=Sirionó |nativename=''Mbia chẽẽ'' |states=[[Bolivia]] |ethnicity=[[Sirionó people]], [[Yuqui people]] |speakers={{sigfig|520|1}} |date=2004 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1 = [[Tupian languages|Tupian]] |fam2 = [[Tupí–Guaraní languages|Tupí–Guaraní]] |fam3 = Guarayu |lc1=srq|ld1=Sirionó |lc2=yuq|ld2=Yuqui (Yúki) |lc3=jor|ld3=Jorá (Hora)<sup>†</sup> |glotto=siri1279|glottoname=Siriono–Jora |glotto2=yuqu1240|glottoname2=Yuqui |notice=IPA }}
'''Sirionó''' (also '''Mbia Chee''', '''Mbya''', '''Siriono''') is a [[Tupian]] (Tupi–Guarani, Subgroup II) language spoken by about 400 [[Sirionó people]] (50 are [[monolingual]]) and 120 Yuqui in eastern [[Bolivia]] (eastern [[Beni Department|Beni]] and northwestern [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz]] departments) in the village of [[Ibiato]] (Eviato) and along the [[Río Blanco (Bolivia)|Río Blanco]] in farms and ranches.
==Phonology==
Sirionó has phonemic contrasts between front, central, and back, close and mid vowels, i.e. {| class="wikitable IPA" |+ Sirionó&nbsp;vowels | i ĩ | ɨ ɨ̃ | u ũ |- | e ẽ | ə ə̃ | o õ |- | | a ã | |}
